Don&#39;t mix padding and margins if you don&#39;t want this behaviour. Use margins everywhere and they will collapse.

If the inner box margin is `1em` and the outer box margin is `10px`, the resulting collapsed margin will be `max(1em; 10px)`:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-css --&gt;

            div.outer {
                width: 300px;
                /*padding: 10px;*/
                border: solid black 1px;
            }
            
            div.inner {
              margin: 10px;
            }

            p {
                margin-top: 1em;
                margin-bottom: 1em;
                border: dotted black 1px;
            }

&lt;!-- language: lang-html --&gt;


      &lt;div class=&quot;outer&quot;&gt;
        &lt;div class=&quot;inner&quot;&gt; &lt;!-- this div will be used only to simulate padding --&gt;
          &lt;p&gt;Paragraph 1&lt;/p&gt;
          &lt;p&gt;Paragraph 2&lt;/p&gt;
          &lt;p&gt;Paragraph 3&lt;/p&gt;
        &lt;/div&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;


---

Reference about collapsing margins:

[MDN](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/CSS_Box_Model/Mastering_margin_collapsing)

[CSS-tricks](https://css-tricks.com/what-you-should-know-about-collapsing-margins/)

You can use :first-child and :last-child on p tag to remove the margin.

 

    p:first-child{
            margin-top:0;
          }
     p:last-child{
            margin-bottom:0;
          }

Here is the demo: [https://codepen.io/NehhaSharma/pen/zYYoQgg][1]


